adams.flow.control.Flow
	-annotation
	This example demonstrates how to use \"recursive\" variables.\nAn example of a recursive variable is as follows:\n   @{@{blah}}\nIf the variable value of \"blah\" is \"hello\" and the variable value \nof \"hello\" is \"7\", then this expression will evaluate as follows:\n   @{@{blah}} -> @{hello} -> 7\nRecursive variables can be set when attaching a variable to \nthe variable name of a SetVariable actor.
	-actor
		adams.flow.source.StringConstants
			-string
			1
			-string
			2
			-string
			3
			-string
			4
			-string
			5
	-actor
		adams.flow.transformer.SetVariable
			-var-name
			num_var
	-actor
		adams.flow.transformer.Convert
			-conversion
				adams.data.conversion.StringToDouble
	-actor
		adams.flow.transformer.MathExpression
			-expression
			X^2
	-actor
		adams.flow.transformer.Convert
			-name
			Convert-1
			-conversion
				adams.data.conversion.MultiConversion
					-conversion
						adams.data.conversion.DoubleToInt
					-conversion
						adams.data.conversion.IntToString
	-actor
		adams.flow.transformer.SetVariable
			-name
			SetVariable-1
			-var-name
			@{num_var}
	-actor
		adams.flow.transformer.StringReplace
			-find
			.*
			-replace
			@{num_var},@{@{num_var}}
			-variable
			true
	-actor
		adams.flow.sink.Display
	-flow-execution-listener
		adams.flow.execution.NullListener

